{"title_page": "Herbert Sawyer (Royal Navy officer, died 1798)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}{{Infobox military person\n|name=Herbert Sawyer\n|birth_date=c. 1730\n|death_date= 4 June 1798\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_place =\n|death_place =[[Bath, Somerset]]\n|nickname=\n|residence =  [[Kingdom of Great Britain]]\n|nationality =  [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]]\n|allegiance={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|serviceyears= 1747\u20131798\n|rank=[[Admiral (United Kingdom)|Admiral]]\n|branch= {{navy|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|commands=[[HMS Happy (1754)|HMS ''Happy'']]<br>[[HMS Swallow (1745)|HMS ''Swallow'']]<br>[[HMS Chesterfield (1745)|HMS ''Chesterfield'']]<br>[[HMS Active (1758)|HMS ''Active'']]<br>[[HMS Boyne (1766)|HMS ''Boyne'']]<br>[[HMS Namur (1756)|HMS ''Namur'']]<br>[[HMS Bombay Castle (1782)|HMS ''Bombay Castle'']]<br>[[North America and West Indies Station|North American Station]]\n|unit=\n|battles=\n*[[Seven Years' War]]\n*[[American War of Independence]]\n**[[Battle of St. Lucia]]\n**[[Battle of Grenada]]\n**[[Great Siege of Gibraltar|Relief of Gibraltar]]\n*[[French Revolutionary Wars]]\n|awards=\n|relations=[[Herbert Sawyer]] (Son)\n}}\n\n'''Herbert Sawyer''' (c. 1730 \u2013 4 June 1798) was an officer of the [[Royal Navy]] who saw service during the [[Seven Years' War]], the [[American War of Independence]] and the [[French Revolutionary Wars]].  He eventually rose to the rank of [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|admiral]].\n\n==Early life==\nLittle is known about Sawyer's early life, but he entered the navy in 1747, spending his first six years mostly on the Jamaica Station aboard [[George Townshend (Royal Navy officer)|George Townshend]]'s [[HMS Gloucester (1745)|HMS ''Gloucester'']].<ref name=\"ODNB\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/24755 Herbert Sawyer at Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]</ref> He passed his [[lieutenant]]'s examination on 30 August 1753, when his age was given as 'more than 22', suggesting he was born in or before 1730. He was promoted to lieutenant on 4 March 1756, and the following year was serving aboard [[HMS Grafton (1750)|HMS ''Grafton'']], which at the time was part of Vice-Admiral [[Francis Holburne]]'s fleet off [[Louisbourg]].<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\n==Promotion to command==\nHe received his first command, that of the [[sloop-of-war|sloop]] [[HMS Happy (1754)|HMS ''Happy'']] on 19 October 1758, but was soon moved to [[HMS Swallow (1745)|HMS ''Swallow'']] off the coast of France under the orders of [[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Lord Howe]].<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  He took command of [[HMS Chesterfield (1745)|HMS ''Chesterfield'']] on 26 December, followed with a transfer to [[HMS Active (1758)|HMS ''Active'']] in February 1759.  He spent the rest of the war aboard her.  On 21 May 1762 he and the sloop [[HMS Favourite (1757)|HMS ''Favourite'']], the latter commanded by [[Philemon Pownoll]], [[Action of 31 May 1762|captured the Spanish treasure ship ''Hermione'']] off [[Cadiz]].  A cargo of over \u00a3500,000 in cash and bullion was secured, of which Sawyer received \u00a365,053 13s. 9d.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  Now extremely wealthy, he married the daughter of a [[Lisbon]] merchant.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nHis next appointment came in 1777, with the command of [[HMS Boyne (1766)|HMS ''Boyne'']].<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  He sailed with her the following year to join Rear-Admiral [[Samuel Barrington]] off the [[West Indies]], and was present at the repulse of [[Charles Hector, comte d'Estaing]]'s attempt [[Battle of St. Lucia|to capture]] [[St Lucia]] on 15 December that year.  Sawyer remained in the Caribbean, and was present at the [[Battle of Grenada]] as part of Vice-Admiral [[John Byron]]'s fleet on 6 July 1779.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  Sawyer returned to England in the autumn, and was given command of [[HMS Namur (1756)|HMS ''Namur'']] in 1780.  He commanded her in the [[English Channel]], and was present at the [[Great Siege of Gibraltar|relief of Gibraltar]] in April 1781.  He left the ''Namur'' in December, and by 1783 he was in command of the [[guardship]] [[HMS Bombay Castle (1782)|HMS ''Bombay Castle'']] at [[Plymouth]].<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\n==On the North American Station==\n[[File:Herbert Sawyer's Daughter Plaque, St Paul's Church, Halifax.jpg|thumb|Monument to Herbert Sawyer's daughter Sophia, d.1788 [[St. Paul's Church (Halifax)]], Nova Scotia]]\nHe left the ''Namur'' in 1785 and was appointed commodore of the [[North America and West Indies Station|North American Station]]'s base at [[City of Halifax|Halifax]].<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  He took up his post in June, and authorized the frigate [[HMS Mercury (1779)|HMS ''Mercury'']] to escort a merchant vessel to the American port of [[Boston]] to collect a shipment of cattle.  This marked the first free visit of a British warship to the port since March 1776.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> In 1787 Sawyer had taken part of his fleet to [[Quebec]], where he was embarrassed by a French squadron of three ships of the line and four frigates, which sailed unchallenged along the [[Nova Scotia]] coast bound for Boston.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> His daughter Sophia died in Halifax in 1788 and was buried in the [[crypt]] at [[St. Paul's Church (Halifax)]]. Soon after he returned to England in August 1788.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\n==Further promotions==\nSawyer never returned to sea but continued to rise through the ranks based on his seniority.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  He was promoted to rear-admiral on 24 September 1788, vice-admiral on 1 February 1793 and admiral on 1 June 1795.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  Poor health meant he was unable to take up any commands.  He died in [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[Somerset]], on 4 June 1798.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  His eldest son, also named [[Herbert Sawyer]] followed his father into a navy, and also had served in the [[American Revolution]]. He too reached the rank of admiral, and even was appointed to his father's old command on the [[North America and West Indies Station|North American Station]], which he commanded during the [[War of 1812]].<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[[J. K. Laughton]], [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/24755 \u2018Sawyer, Herbert (b. in or before 1730, d. 1798)\u2019], rev. Julian Gwyn, ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', [[Oxford University Press]], 2004, {{doi|10.1093/ref:odnb/24755}} accessed 30 June 2008 (also mentions younger Herbert Sawyer). {{DNBfirst|wstitle=Sawyer, Herbert}}\n*{{Colledge}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box|title=[[North America and West Indies Station|Commander-in-Chief, North American Station]]|before=[[Sir Charles Douglas, 1st Baronet|Sir Charles Douglas]]|after=[[Sir Richard Hughes, 2nd Baronet|Sir Richard Hughes]]|years=1785\u20131789}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sawyer, Herbert}}\n[[Category:1730 births]]\n[[Category:1798 deaths]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Seven Years' War]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the American Revolutionary War]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the French Revolutionary Wars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}{{Infobox military person\n|name=Herbert Sawyer\n|birth_date=c. 1730\n|death_date= 4 June 1798\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_place =\n|death_place =[[Bath, Somerset]]\n|nickname=\n|residence =  [[Kingdom of Great Britain]]\n|nationality =  [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]]\n|allegiance={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|serviceyears= 1747\u20131798\n|rank=[[Admiral (United Kingdom)|Admiral]]\n|branch= {{navy|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|commands=[[HMS Happy (1754)|HMS ''Happy'']]<br>[[HMS Swallow (1745)|HMS ''Swallow'']]<br>[[HMS Chesterfield (1745)|HMS ''Chesterfield'']]<br>[[HMS Active (1758)|HMS ''Active'']]<br>[[HMS Boyne (1766)|HMS ''Boyne'']]<br>[[HMS Namur (1756)|HMS ''Namur'']]<br>[[HMS Bombay Castle (1782)|HMS ''Bombay Castle'']]<br>[[North America and West Indies Station|North American Station]]\n|unit=\n|battles=\n*[[Seven Years' War]]\n*[[American War of Independence]]\n**[[Battle of St. Lucia]]\n**[[Battle of Grenada]]\n**[[Great Siege of Gibraltar|Relief of Gibraltar]]\n*[[French Revolutionary Wars]]\n|awards=\n|relations=[[Herbert Sawyer]] (Son)\n}}\n\n'''Herbert Sawyer''' (c. 1730 \u2013 4 June 1798) was an officer of the [[Royal Navy]] who saw service during the [[Seven Years' War]], the [[American War of Independence]] and the [[French Revolutionary Wars]].  He eventually rose to the rank of [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|admiral]].\n\n==Early life==\nLittle is known about Sawyer's early life, but he entered the navy in 1747, spending his first six years mostly on the Jamaica Station aboard [[George Townshend (Royal Navy officer)|George Townshend]]'s [[HMS Gloucester (1745)|HMS ''Gloucester'']].<ref name=\"ODNB\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/24755 Herbert Sawyer at Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]</ref> He passed his [[lieutenant]]'s examination on 30 August 1753, when his age was given as 'more than 22', suggesting he was born in or before 1730. He was promoted to lieutenant on 4 March 1756, and the following year was serving aboard [[HMS Grafton (1750)|HMS ''Grafton'']], which at the time was part of Vice-Admiral [[Francis Holburne]]'s fleet off [[Louisbourg]].<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\n==Promotion to command==\nHe received his first command, that of the [[sloop-of-war|sloop]] [[HMS Happy (1754)|HMS ''Happy'']] on 19 October 1758, but was soon moved to [[HMS Swallow (1745)|HMS ''Swallow'']] off the coast of France under the orders of [[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Lord Howe]].<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  He took command of [[HMS Chesterfield (1745)|HMS ''Chesterfield'']] on 26 December, followed with a transfer to [[HMS Active (1758)|HMS ''Active'']] in February 1759.  He spent the rest of the war aboard her.  On 21 May 1762 he and the sloop [[HMS Favourite (1757)|HMS ''Favourite'']], the latter commanded by [[Phil